name=&quot;XE_Index_Entry_Category___New_Guideline&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;a id=&quot;Introduction&quot; name=&quot;Introduction&quot;>&lt;/a>In the inception phase, the focus is twofold. One emphasis is on&#xD;
    identifying and determining the architectural and design constraints imposed on the candidate solutions by any&#xD;
    infrastructure on which the solution will run and any other systems with which the solution must interact. The overall&#xD;
    context in which the new solution must operate must be captured.This context includes legacy capabilities with which&#xD;
    the new solution shares data.Thesecond focus is on identifying potential architectural alternatives that might be&#xD;
    applicable.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The important areas of work in this sphere are:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;p>&#xD;
            &lt;b>Determine architectural context&lt;/b>: The purpose is to understand the architectural context for the solution&#xD;
            in sufficient detail to ensure that each candidate solution developed in response to the identified stakeholder&#xD;
            needs will operate in the context of the larger organization. This also involves identifying architecture&#xD;
            constraints, boundaries and interfaces posed by external systems with which the solution must interface. This&#xD;
            information is captured in the current and To-Be &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot;&#xD;
            href=&quot;./../../extend.bus_model/workproducts/rup_business_analysis_model_9449F63A.html&quot;&#xD;
            guid=&quot;{CF53445C-3351-46C6-810E-8251830029A7}&quot;>Business Analysis Models&lt;/a> and current and To-Be &lt;a&#xD;
            class=&quot;elementLinkWithUserText&quot;&#xD;
            href=&quot;./../../extend.bus_model/workproducts/rup_business_architecture_document_A73E67D4.html&quot;&#xD;
            guid=&quot;{D3A0CA96-30AD-4461-9386-A3EC9A7E879F}&quot;>Business Architecture Documents&lt;/a>.&#xD;
        &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;p>&#xD;
            &lt;b>Identify architectural alternatives&lt;/b>: The purpose is to formulate potential architectural alternatives by&#xD;
            identifying generic architectural patterns that might be applicable. Architectural patterns are captured in the&#xD;
            To-Be &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../extend.bus_model/workproducts/rup_business_analysis_model_9449F63A.html&quot;&#xD;
            guid=&quot;{CF53445C-3351-46C6-810E-8251830029A7}&quot;>Business Analysis Model&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;and To-Be &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
            href=&quot;./../../extend.bus_model/workproducts/rup_business_architecture_document_A73E67D4.html&quot;&#xD;
            guid=&quot;{D3A0CA96-30AD-4461-9386-A3EC9A7E879F}&quot;>Business Architecture Document&lt;/a>.&#xD;
        &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Determining architecture context and identifying architectural alternatives is done by performing the RUP task shown in&#xD;
    the following figure (note that other RUP tasks and artifacts of the business modeling and analysis &amp;amp; design&#xD;
    disciplines may be applicable, but this is the minimum recommended set):&#xD;
